******
[2] Uganda (Kasese)
Date: Thu 13 Nov 2008
Source: AllAfrica, New Vision (Kampala) report [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200811130072.html>


In the last 4 months, 20 people have died and 90 others admitted
following a typhoid outbreak in Kasese district in western Uganda.
The latest deaths were of 4 people, who died last week [week of 3 Nov
2008] in Kyabarungira sub-county. The sub-county chief, Steven Kabau,
said the dead included 2 students of Kuruhe High School, a Primary
Six pupil of Kyabarungira Primary School and a catering graduate.

The district health officer, Dr Peter Mukobi, said: "More people are
believed to have died of typhoid, though their cases have not been reported."

Mukobi said it was difficult to diagnose typhoid. He added, "The
problem with typhoid is that patients show symptoms of malaria at the
beginning. In most cases, by the time one realizes that it is typhoid
it is too late," Mukobi explained.

[Byline: Conan Businge, John Thawite]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[Uganda's Kasese district is located in the southwestern part of the
country and can be found on a map at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/uganda.pdf>.
The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Uganda is available at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?g=443342&v=0.167,30,6>.

Both these postings state the difficulty of distinguishing typhoid
fever, a waterborne bacterial disease caused by _Salmonella enterica_
serotype Typhi and malaria, a mosquito-borne protozoan infection
caused a one of several species of _Plasmodium_. Both illnesses, as
well as a number of other infections, present as primarily febrile
episodes without, necessarily, any symptoms suggesting involvement of
a specific organ system.

Typhoid fever is best diagnosed by bacterial culture of the blood or
by serological methods and can be treated with one of a variety of
antibacterial agents. Malaria is best diagnosed by examining a
stained smear of the peripheral blood looking for the
intraerythrocytic protozoa and is treated with one or a combination
of antimalarials. In the absence of laboratory facilities, the
periodic fever of malaria (every 2nd or 3rd day) and the
non-remitting fever of typhoid may help to distinguish the illnesses
although neither may be present early in the illness. - Mod.LL]
